# SPEC — [Project Name]

> Initial specification. Written by the human, refined with AI assistance.
> This is the "brain dump" that drives Phase A of the workflow.
> Omit sections that don't apply. A 30-line spec for a utility is better than 150 lines with filler.

## Scope & value

[What problem does this solve? For whom? Describe a concrete scenario — a real user doing a real thing.
What is explicitly OUT OF SCOPE for this version?]

## Decisions & rationale

[Tech stack with WHY each choice was made. Architecture pattern and why it fits.
Key trade-offs acknowledged.]

## Executable detail

[Exact commands: build, test, run, deploy — copy-paste ready.
Data model: entities, fields, relationships, constraints.
Project structure if non-obvious.]

## Hard constraints

[Concrete numbers: "p95 response < 200ms", "Chrome 120+, Safari 17+".
Security requirements. Compatibility. Budget/timeline if relevant.]

## Business logic

[Rules with concrete examples: IF order > 500 EUR AND new customer THEN require manual approval.
Calculation formulas with test values. Decision trees. Edge cases with expected behavior.]

## Acceptance criteria

[GIVEN [context] WHEN [action] THEN [result] — for each key behavior.
Test strategy: unit, integration, e2e. What "done" looks like.]

## Domain pitfalls

[What looks right but is wrong. Previous failed approaches and why they failed.
Promising solution directions to explore. Environment-specific quirks.]
